<dl id="n20218a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n20" href="#n20218a">N20 (VI.B.13)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n20all.htm#n20218a"> 218(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> placing thumb to / nose in / New Cut fashion</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The <cite>Athen&aelig;um</cite> on a performance of <cite>Acis and Galatea</cite>]</font> The Polyphemous of Mr. Phillips was &ldquo;fairly sung &hellip;. But when we say that while listening to Damon &hellip; he all but laid his thumb to his nose after the polite fashion of the New Cut, we have indicated the amount of classicality in his conception of the part.&rdquo; <small> Charles E. Pearce, <a name="CEPS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CEPS"><cite title="source">Sims Reeves: Fifty Years of Music in England</cite></a> (Jun 1924) 45</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
